From this perspective, investigations on the electronic structural properties of CQDs reveal that their bandgap depends on their particle size and composition [84,85,118,133–137]. It is well known that the effect of quantum confinement increases as the size of CQDs decreases, resulting in a blue-shift characteristic of both absorption and emission spectra (see Fig. 2
                     (a and b and c)). State-of-the-art theoretical electronic structure methods have been widely used to describe the absorption/emission spectra of CQDs of different particle sizes, shapes and compositions [138–140]. In addition, many surface functional groups strongly moderate the highest occupied molecular orbital (HOMO) and lowest unoccupied molecular orbital (LUMO) levels of CQDs [140–143]. Particularly, the HOMO/LUMO energy gap changes with size, thereby inducing significant changes in the absorption/emission spectra [144]. Thus, changes in the CQD surfaces strongly affect their electronic properties, and such alterations, in principle, can be performed in both solution and solid films [145–147]. These results reveal that the addition of electron-donating functional groups increases the HOMO and LUMO energy levels of the CQDs, whereas the addition of electron-withdrawing functional groups causes a decrease [140,142]. In particular, carbonyl groups appear to be the more suitable for modifying the electronic and optical properties of CQDs because they reduce energy levels of carbonyl π-electrons [142,143]. In this case, the decrease in the HOMO energy is lesser than in the LUMO energy, leading to a smaller energy gap. On the other hand, the electron transfer from the amino group is larger than from carbonyl group, which could result in a higher exciton binding energy and quasiparticle correction for the amino group. Thus, the hybridised frontier orbitals of the amino groups increase the energy gap [142]. Fig. 2 (d) depicts the multicolor fluorescent CQDs prepared by means of the electron-donating/withdrawing group-engineering route [148]. Furthermore, it has been reported that n-type and p-type doping on the bases of CQDs with a large-radius atom plane can transform the sp2-hybridised carbon into the sp3 state [149]. The optical behaviour of CQDs has been widely investigated owing to the high PLQY values typically observed (see Table 1
                     ) [98,99,150–152]. It is crucial to highlight that the materials compared in this study were synthesized using different routes and precursors (which results in sample heterogeneity). Given that materials processing inherently involves defect engineering, the experimental conditions employed during manufacturing can significantly influence the number and type of defects in the final product. Consequently, materials with similar physical attributes, such as morphology, size, composition, and structure, can exhibit vastly different properties when produced through distinct synthetic pathways [84,85,153,154]. In general, high PLQY values are of great importance in various CQD-based applications, such as bioimaging, sensing, solar cells, and photodynamic therapy [98,99,150–152]. The UV–vis spectra of CQDs exhibit absorption peaks in the range of 280–400 nm, which are associated with the typical n-π* transition of the CO band and the π-π* transition of the conjugated CC [155,156]. However, it has been demonstrated that the presence of the polar functional groups on CQD surfaces can induce an absorbance in the visible range as a function of their composition [157–159]. During passivation, π and π* states are created, resulting in an increase in the charge density by electron donation for the sp2 hybrid domain. The outcome is an increase in the energy levels at the CQDs surface; consequently, the bandwidth is narrowed [17]. On the other hand, the relationship between the particle size of CQDs and their PL properties has been extensively explored in the literature [31]. Beyond the particle size effect, it has also been observed that modulation of the CQD surface states greatly influence their optical responses [160–164]. As depicted in Fig. 2(b and c), the CQD surface states are responsible for the creation of distinct excitonic absorption bands and PL emissions, which are critical for understanding their molecular behaviour. It has been reported that at room temperature, CQDs exhibit strong fluorescence with a long lifetime [165–168]. Understanding these properties is essential for tailoring CQDs to specific applications and advancing technologies in fields ranging from medicine to photonics.
